SIMPLE: thud
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thud
<hw>Thud</hw> <pr>(th⟦ucr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧den</ets> a whirlwind, violent wind, or E.
<ets>thump</ets>.]</ety> <def>A dull sound without resonance, like that
produced by striking with, or striking against, some comparatively soft
substance; also, the stroke or blow producing such sound; <as>as, the
<ex>thrud</ex> of a cannon ball striking the earth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At every new <qex>thud</qex> of the blast, a sob arose.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At intervals there came some tremendous <qex>thud</qex> on the
side of the steamer.</q> <rj><qau>C. Mackay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thud
<hw>Thud</hw> <pr>(th⟦ucr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <def>To make,
or strike so as to make, a dull sound, or thud.</def></p>

<p><q>Hardly the softest <qex>thudding</qex> of velvety pads.</q>
<rj><qau>A. C. Doyle.</qau></rj></p>

<p><q>The waves break into spray, dash and rumble and <qex>thud</qex>
below your feet.</q> <rj><qau>H. F. Brown.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thug</ent>⟦br⟧
